name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Speaking of new instructional patterns: the "academy" idea of having a 6th grade academy means re-evaluating the curriculum pathway. Students can decide what pathway they want to take, such as health sciences, robotics.

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Why the new feeder pattern? It was all about instructional planning for Dr. Douglas.

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Again, no zone lines change. These are the same kids who would be together starting in ninth grade. We want to get them together sooner.

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Students will get with their "group" at 6th grade. Students who go through middle school together will no longer be split up when it's time to transition to high school.

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: District lines won't change. Students who are zoned to go to Austin will still go to Austin. Students currently zoned to go to Decatur will go to Decatur.

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: "I don't know of any AL school system with multiple high schools that doesn't have a clean feeder pattern. Jefferson County, Huntsville City, Madison... no one but us."

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Vertical planning is all about transition grades‚Äîwhen students move from one school to the next. It's easier to make teaching plans when your 6th graders are all of the kids from a few elementary schools.

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Live tweeting tonight's community meeting about proposed feeder pattern changes! Coming live from @DHSRaiders.

tweet: Need more info? Email questions/concerns to feederpattern@dcs.edu, come to next meeting at @DHSRaiders next week.

tweet: "I want your input; I really do. ...I want to do what's best for all. What's fair." -Dr. Douglas

name: Decatur City Schools
tweet: Clean feeder patterns let students stay with their friends all the way through school‚Äîand let teachers make better plans for instruction.

tweet: All other school districts in the state have direct feeder patterns‚Äîstudents stay with the same group from elementary through high school.
